# Dataset Card: Unit Tests

## Overview

The `datasets/unit_tests/` folder contains datasets specifically designed to verify the correctness, consistency, and reliability of Circuit-Bench dataset processing functions. These datasets support automated testing by providing controlled inputs with known expected outputs.

---

## Purpose

The unit test datasets are intended to:

- Verify dataset loading functions
- Validate preprocessing pipelines
- Test parsers and converters
- Ensure metadata consistency
- Detect regressions after code changes
- Support continuous integration (CI) testing

---

## Intended Applications

These datasets are suitable for:

- Automated unit testing
- Continuous integration (CI)
- Regression testing
- Dataset validation
- Software quality assurance
- Benchmark pipeline verification

---

## Folder Organization

A typical directory structure may resemble:

```text
unit_tests/
├── analog/
├── digital/
├── passive/
├── active/
├── rf/
├── power_electronics/
├── malformed/
├── expected_outputs/
├── metadata/
└── README.md
```

The structure may evolve as additional benchmark tasks and testing scenarios are introduced.

---

## Dataset Contents

Unit test datasets may include:

- Small circuit netlists
- Synthetic benchmark circuits
- Ground-truth labels
- Metadata files
- Reference outputs
- Edge-case examples
- Invalid or malformed datasets
- Test fixtures

---

## Testing Objectives

These datasets are used to verify:

- Dataset loading
- File parsing
- Metadata extraction
- Label integrity
- Schema compliance
- Error handling
- Data normalization
- Output consistency

---

## Quality Assurance

Each unit test dataset should undergo:

- Manual verification
- Schema validation
- Metadata validation
- Duplicate detection
- File integrity verification
- Expected output verification

---

## Recommended Usage

Developers are encouraged to:

- Execute unit tests after modifying dataset utilities.
- Keep test datasets lightweight for fast execution.
- Use deterministic test cases.
- Clearly document expected outputs.
- Maintain compatibility across supported software versions.

---

## Example Testing Workflow

```text
Unit Test Dataset
        │
        ▼
Dataset Loader
        │
        ▼
Preprocessing Pipeline
        │
        ▼
Validation Checks
        │
        ▼
Expected Output Comparison
        │
        ▼
Pass / Fail Result
```

---

## Best Practices

Users should:

- Keep unit test datasets independent of training and evaluation datasets.
- Include representative edge cases.
- Avoid unnecessary dataset complexity.
- Update expected outputs when intentional changes are introduced.
- Version-control all testing datasets.

---

## Limitations

Unit test datasets are intentionally small and controlled. They may not:

- Represent real-world dataset diversity
- Capture all circuit topologies
- Evaluate model performance
- Replace integration or system testing

Comprehensive testing should combine unit, integration, and benchmark evaluations.

